      <summary>Flat Tires</summary>
      <h2>How to fix a flat tire</h2>
      <p></p>
   <a href="https://imgur.com/o0pSjv8"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/o0pSjv8.png" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
      <p>Whether you’re riding on smooth pavement, gravel, or single-track trails, at some point your bike will get a flat. This means you need to prepare yourself with both the necessary tools and knowledge required to mend the situation.
      <br>
      <br>
        Below, we detail everything you may need to know to fix a flat tire. For tools, you should always carry tire levers, a correctly sized spare tube, and an inflation device. You may also want to have a patch kit or tire plug equipped, which come in handy for certain riders.
      </p>
        <iframe width="400" height="300" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/qLO_HO0kEjs" frameborder="0" allow="accelerometer; autoplay; encrypted-media; gyroscope; picture-in-picture" allowfullscreen></iframe>

      <h3>Remove/Plug the Tire </h3>
      <p>Normally, your first priority in the event of a flat is to remove the tire so that you can assess the problem inside. However as tubeless setups are becoming more popular across most bike models—you can often stop air loss with a tire plug. These kits typically come with a small strip of rubber and insertion device. Allowing you to plug the hole without additional hardware. Once you spot the hole and insert the rubber plug, re-inflate your tire to the appropriate pressure and check to see if it’s holding air. If so you’re all set to start riding again! </p>
       <a href="https://imgur.com/H4I0d1G"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/H4I0d1G.jpg" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
      <p>
        If plugging the tire doesn’t work, or perhaps you’re not riding tubeless, you’ll need to remove the wheel. Keep your bike upright, and if it’s a rear wheel flat, shift the drivetrain into the hardest gear. You may also need to loosen the brake if you have rim brakes. Next, position yourself on the non-drive side of your bike (opposite the chain) and either open the quick release or unthread the thru-axle to remove the wheel.
        <br>
        <br>
        Now remove the tire. Hook the rounded end of one tire level under the bead (outer edge) of the tire to unseat it. Affix the other end to a spoke to hold the lever in place and keep the unseated tire from popping back into the rim. Then you want to hook the second lever under the bead next to the first, walking around the rim clockwise until one side of the tire is off. No need to completely remove the tire! </p>
      <h3> Find the Cause </h3>
      <p>Once you’ve removed the tire, pull out the old tube and look for the source of the flat. This could be a piece of glass, thorn, or some other sharp object. Slowly run your fingers along the inside of the tire and rim to make sure nothing sharp is left behind. Also be sure to inspect the exterior of the tire, looking for any foreign object that might still be lodged in the rubber. If you’re using tubes a shortcut would be to pump some air into the old tire to find the leak. </p>

      <h3>Patch it up! </h3>
      <p>
It is now possible to patch your tube with a patch kit. Begin by cleaning the punctured area and drying the surface with a cloth. For a glue-less patch, simply stick it over the hole and press firmly. For a patch that requires glue just add a thin layer of it to the tube and patch. Firmly press the patch after the glue sticks.
      </p>
    <a href="https://imgur.com/vsPFNEG"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/vsPFNEG.jpg" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
      <h3> Install the Tube </h3>
      <p>Now is the time to inflate your newly patched tube so that it holds its shape. Next, with the valve stem installed straight through the rim’s valve hole, work the tire back onto the rim with your hands by rolling the bead away from your position. When you get the valve to the stem, tuck both sides of tire bead low into the rim, pushing it upward on the stem to get the tube inside.  Check to ensure the tire bead isn’t pinching the tube and then inflate to the appropriate level. If everything looks good at this point reattach your wheel, keeping the quick release lever on the opposite side of the drivetrain.
        <br>
        <br>
        If you experienced a rear flat, lay the top of the chain around the smallest cog on your cassette and carefully push the wheel back into the frame. Then close the quick release into the frame and hold until closed. Lastly, lift the rear wheel and spin the cranks to ensure things are operating smoothly. </p>






