     <summary>Adjusting Rim and Disc Plates</summary>
  <p> We're all bound to deal with tight, squeaky, or misaligned brakes at some point during our time on our bicycles. However most of these fixes are ones that can be done on the fly.
  </p>
  <h3>Disc Brakes </h3>
  <p> Disc brakes happen to be quite easy to adjust. Start by loosening the two bolts that mount the disc brake to the frame. Once they're loose, squeeze the brakes so that the rotor is engaged. It is now centered perfectly, so--with the brake levers still depressed--re tighten those bolts.
  </p>
    <br>
  <h3>Rim Brakes</h3>
  <p> Start by using what's in place already: the barrel adjuster that's at the top of the brake lever cable. Just tightening or loosening this can solve a lot of common issues.
    <br>
    <br>
    If that is unsuccessful you can check the bolt where the brake is connected to the frame. When the bolt isn't tight enough, it can cause your entire brake to move as you ride. So engage the brakes and then tighten that bolt so it's centered.
    <br>
    If your brakes are too loose--meaning you need to pull the levers too hard to engage them--slightly tighten the cable.

 <br>
    When trying to adjust the brake pads to hit the same spot on the rim on either side, tighten the brakes with the arrel adjuster first. Once the pads are tight to the rim, loosening the bolt that keeps them in place to make minor adjustments becomes possible. </p>
