        <summary>Pumping Bike Tires</summary>
        <p>Tires need the right amount of air to function properly, but getting them to the right psi efficiently can require some effort. </p>

        <h3>Choose the Right Bike Pump</h3>
        <a href="https://imgur.com/BQqJMCa"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/BQqJMCa.png" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
        <br>
        <p>A common mistake new and experienced riders make when pumping their tires is using the incorrect bike pump valve.
          <br>
          There are two popular tube vavles: A Schrader valve is wider and flat on the end, while a Presta valve is narrower and features a locking nut, which can be loosened to add or release air. An easy way to remember the difference is that with a Presta you press to let air out. </p>

        <h3>Prepare the Valve</h3>
        <a href="https://imgur.com/v2GpMnw"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/v2GpMnw.jpg" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
        <p>
        First, remove the plastic cap that might be covering the end of your valve. Then unscrew the tiny locking nut. </p>
        <h3> Know the Tire Pressure You Need </h3>
<a href="https://imgur.com/AU53gSM"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/AU53gSM.jpg" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
        <p>Before pumping, check the sidewall of your tire: It should list the pounds-per-square-inch (psi) range that your tire can safely handle. A typical road tire can go between 80 and 130 psi, while a mountain tire holds between 30 and 50 psi. Hybrids run between 50 and 70 psi. Where your personal psi preference falls will depend on your weight and riding style. It is suggested you play around with these figures until you find the right psi for you. </p>
        <h3>Attach the Pump Correctly </h3>
        <a href="https://imgur.com/P6u34iX"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/P6u34iX.jpg" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
        <p>Fit the pump head onto the valve. they will have either a switch that flips down or up, or an interally threaded screw top. Both serve to keep the head in place as you start pumping, ensuring air goes into the valve.
          <br>
          If air seems to be coming out of the pump and not into your tires, you many need to adjust the pump head slightly. Just detach and reattach to reset the seal. </p>
        <h3> Pump to Optimal Pressure </h3>
        <a href="https://imgur.com/OBRMtqV"><img src="https://i.imgur.com/OBRMtqV.jpg" title="source: imgur.com" /></a>
        <p>Utilizing the gauge on your pump to guide you, pump the tubes up to your optimal pressure. Once you've pumped your tires to the pressure you want, simply flip the switch on the pump head so it comes off, and regithten the locking nut before you replace the valve cap.</p>
